# Origin Browser

A minimal, keyboard‑driven desktop web browser for Windows, built from the ground up with **C# WinForms + Microsoft Edge WebView2**.  
Origin is fast, private, and completely yours—no telemetry, no bloat, no surveillance.

**Start page:** [origin.mozartt.workers.dev](https://origin.mozartt.workers.dev)  
**Repository:** [github.com/Initial-Mozartt/Origin-Browser](https://github.com/Initial-Mozartt/Origin-Browser)

---

## Why Origin?

Most browsers are designed for everyone—meaning they’re also designed to mine your data. Origin is different. It’s a personal tool, crafted for a single user who values speed, control, and a distraction‑free workflow.

- **Zero telemetry** – No Google, no Microsoft, no phoning home.
- **Keyboard‑first** – Nearly every action has a shortcut; you never need a mouse.
- **Built‑in terminal** – PowerShell, CMD, WSL, or Git Bash inside the browser window.
- **Frameless & chrome‑free** – Toggle the title bar, tabs, and address bar independently to get a pure content view.
- **Self‑contained** – A single `.exe` (and a `chrome-ui` folder) is all you need.
- **Open source** – MIT‑licensed, free forever.

---

## Features

### Core Browsing
- **Multi‑tab browsing** – Isolated WebView2 environments per tab; open, close, and switch with keyboard shortcuts.
- **Omnibox** – Type a URL or a search query; automatically sends searches to Google.
- **Session restore** – All tabs are saved on exit and restored on launch (can be disabled).
- **History** – Every visited URL is recorded locally; never leaves your machine.
- **Dark theme** – CSS‑custom properties make everything easy on the eyes.

### Keyboard Shortcuts
| Shortcut | Action |
|----------|--------|
| `Ctrl+T` | New browser tab |
| `Ctrl+W` | Close current browser tab |
| `Ctrl+L` | Focus address bar |
| `Ctrl+R` / `F5` | Reload page |
| `Ctrl+H` | Go to home page (Origin start) |
| `Ctrl+Left` / `Ctrl+[` | Back |
| `Ctrl+Right` / `Ctrl+]` | Forward |
| `Ctrl+Tab` | Next tab |
| `Ctrl+Shift+Tab` | Previous tab |
| `j` / `k` | Scroll down / up (Vim‑style) |
| `Ctrl+d` / `Ctrl+u` | Scroll half‑page down / up |
| `g` / `G` | Scroll to top / bottom |
| `F11` | Toggle full screen |
| `Ctrl+Shift+T` | Toggle integrated terminal |
| `Ctrl+Alt+F` | Toggle title bar (frameless window) |
| `Ctrl+Shift+B` | Toggle browser chrome (tabs + address bar) |
| `Ctrl+Shift+Alt+F` | Full frameless (title bar + chrome off) |

**Note:** Vim‑style scrolling is disabled inside text inputs and textareas.

### Integrated Terminal (`Ctrl+Shift+T`)
- **Multi‑tab terminal** – Create multiple shells (PowerShell, CMD, WSL, Git Bash).
- **xterm.js‑based** – A real terminal emulator with full VT‑100 support, colors, and scrolling.
- **Shortcuts inside the terminal:**
  - `Ctrl+Shift+N` – New terminal tab
  - `Ctrl+Shift+W` – Close terminal tab
  - `Ctrl+Shift+K` – Clear terminal
  - `Ctrl+Shift+R` – Restart current terminal tab
  - `Ctrl++` / `Ctrl+-` / `Ctrl+0` – Increase, decrease, reset font size
  - `Ctrl+Shift+F` – Search in terminal
  - `F3` / `Shift+F3` – Next/previous search match
- **Persistent profiles** – The list of open terminal tabs (but not their output) is restored across sessions.
- **Drag‑to‑resize** – Drag the handle at the top of the terminal panel to resize it.

### Frameless & Chrome Control
You have full control over how the browser looks:

- **Title bar only** (`Ctrl+Alt+F`) – Remove or restore the Windows title bar.
- **Chrome visibility** (`Ctrl+Shift+B`) – Hide or show the custom browser UI (tabs, address bar, buttons) independently.
- **Full frameless** (`Ctrl+Shift+Alt+F`) – Toggle both the title bar and the browser chrome with one shortcut.
- When frameless and chrome‑hidden, you can still **drag the window** from the top strip and **resize** from the edges/corners.

### Settings & Persistence
- All preferences (home page URL, session restore, frameless state, chrome visibility, terminal profiles) are stored in `%LocalAppData%\OriginBrowser\settings.json`.
- The settings file is human‑readable JSON. You can edit it by hand or through the future Settings UI.

---

## Architecture

OriginBrowser/
├── OriginBrowser.csproj # .NET 8 project file
├── Program.cs # Application entry point
├── BrowserForm.cs # Main form: tab management, shortcuts, chrome, terminal
├── TerminalPanel.cs # Terminal panel with xterm.js integration
├── OriginSettings.cs # JSON settings manager
├── chrome-ui/ # Custom HTML/CSS/JS browser chrome
│ ├── index.html
│ ├── style.css
│ └── app.js
├── terminal-ui/ # Terminal frontend
│ ├── terminal.html
│ └── vendor/xterm/ # xterm.js library (offline)
└── chrome-ui/ # Also contains icons, etc.


- **WinForms** handles the window, tabs, and keyboard shortcuts.
- **WebView2** renders both the custom browser chrome (tabs, address bar) and every web page.
- **HTML/CSS/JS** powers the entire browser UI; you can customize it without touching C#.
- **xterm.js** provides the terminal emulation inside a separate WebView2 panel.

---

## Prerequisites

- **Windows 10** (build 1709 or later) or **Windows 11**  
- **WebView2 Runtime** – preinstalled on Windows 11 and most up‑to‑date Windows 10 machines. If missing, download the [Evergreen Bootstrapper](https://developer.microsoft.com/en-us/microsoft-edge/webview2/).
- **.NET 8 SDK** – [Download](https://dotnet.microsoft.com/download/dotnet/8.0) (Windows x64).

---

## Build & Run (from source)

```bash
cd OriginBrowser
dotnet build
dotnet run
To create a standalone, self‑contained OriginBrowser.exe (no .NET runtime required by the user):

bash
dotnet publish -c Release -r win-x64 --self-contained true -p:PublishSingleFile=true -o ./publish
The publish folder (publish/) will contain OriginBrowser.exe and the chrome-ui/ and terminal-ui/ folders. Zip them together for distribution.

Customization
Change the home page – Edit OriginSettings.cs (default: https://origin.mozartt.workers.dev) or modify the HomePageUrl entry in settings.json.

Modify the look – The browser chrome is just HTML/CSS/JS. Edit the files in chrome-ui/ to change colors, layout, or add new features.

Add new shortcuts – All shortcuts are defined in BrowserForm.cs (in ProcessCmdKey) and in the injected page scripts. You can add your own combinations.

Add a new terminal profile – Extend the TerminalPanel.cs shell‑detection logic and update terminal.html’s menu.

